1.Businesss Understanding¶

1.1 Introduction¶

Although many people choose to make payment by card or electronic money, coins still play an important role in our lives. They appear at parking lots, printing centers, supermarkets and other daily expenses. Not only individual purchases need coins, financial organizations such as banks or charities also are facing large amount of coins. According to TitleMax, nowadays there are over 28 billion value coins in general circulation (https://www.titlemax.com/discovery-center/money-finance/how-many-dollar-bill-circulated/).

1.2 Data Description¶

In this project we use a Brazilian coins dataset which was collected by Luis Moneda and posted on Kaggle (https://www.kaggle.com/lgmoneda/br-coins).The dataset we used contains 3000 single-coin images. Those single-coin images present several examples of 5 centavos, 10 centavos, 25 centavos, 50 centavos and 1 real (will be noted as 100 centavos in this project). This dataset is perfect for our need and we would like to use this dataset to train our classification model. Each image has a size of 640x480 pixel. All images are created against a white background, some of them with notable differences in illumination.

1.3 Study Purpose¶

The algorithm we developed could be widely used for coin sorting, coin changing machines such as Coinstar and vending machines. The reason for using Brazilian coins is that some of Brazilian coins don’t have large differences in their size. That means the algorithm we developed could also be applied to sorting any other types of coins like Dollars or Euros. We identify a coin’s value by its image instead of by size.With a high accuracy in classification produced by the algorithm, the coin counting machine should be able to sort the coins by their values at first, count, even summarize the coins’ information at next. Once the value of a coin is recorded, further choices could be made by their customer.

Read in the images as Numpy arrays. The original image was in RGB form. And we transfer the images to greyscale image.

In [6]:
file_name_typenew = [f for f in os.listdir(newpath) if os.path.getsize(os.path.join(newpath, f))!=0]
def rgb2gray(rgb):
    return np.dot(rgb[...,:3], [0.299, 0.587, 0.114])
img_data = np.zeros((size, 19200))

for i in range(size):
    path_rd = os.path.join(newpath +'/' + file_name_typenew[i])
    if path_rd != newpath + '/' + '.DS_Store':
        img = mpimg.imread(path_rd)
        gray = rgb2gray(img)
        farr = gray.flatten()
        img_data[i] = farr      
    else:  
        continue

# a helper plotting function
def plot_gallery(images, titles, h, w, n_row=3, n_col=5):
    """Helper function to plot a gallery of portraits"""
    plt.figure(figsize=(2 * n_col, 2 * n_row))
    plt.subplots_adjust(bottom=0, left=.01, right=.99, top=.90, hspace=.35)
    for i in range(n_row * n_col):
        plt.subplot(n_row, n_col, i + 1)
        plt.imshow(images[i].reshape((h, w)), cmap=plt.cm.gray)
        plt.title(titles[i], size=12)
        plt.xticks(())
        plt.yticks(())
        
labels =  [file_name_type[i] for i in range(size)]

def plot_explained_variance(pca):
    import plotly.offline 
    import plotly
    from plotly.graph_objs import Scatter, Marker, Layout, XAxis, YAxis, Bar, Line
    plotly.offline.init_notebook_mode(connected=True) # run at the start of every notebook
    
    explained_var = pca.explained_variance_ratio_
    cum_var_exp = np.cumsum(explained_var)
    
    plotly.offline.iplot({
        "data": [Bar(y=explained_var, name='individual explained variance'),
                 Scatter(y=cum_var_exp, name='cumulative explained variance')
            ],
        "layout": Layout(xaxis=XAxis(title='Principal components'), yaxis=YAxis(title='Explained variance ratio'))
    })

idx = np.random.choice(df.shape[0])
def plot_reconstruction_comparison(data, idx, pca, rpca, kpca):
    orig = df.iloc[idx].values.reshape(1,-1)
    pca_restruct = pca.inverse_transform(pca.transform(orig))
    rpca_restruct = rpca.inverse_transform(rpca.transform(orig))
    kpca_restruct = kpca.inverse_transform(kpca.transform(orig))
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2)
    
    ax[0][0].imshow(orig.reshape(120,160), cmap=plt.cm.gray)
    ax[0][0].set_title('Original Image')
    ax[0][0].set_xticks(())
    ax[0][0].set_yticks(())

    
    ax[0][1].imshow(pca_restruct.reshape(120,160), cmap=plt.cm.gray)
    ax[0][1].set_title('PCA Reconstruction')
    ax[0][1].set_xticks(())
    ax[0][1].set_yticks(())
    
    ax[1][0].imshow(rpca_restruct.reshape(120,160), cmap=plt.cm.gray)
    ax[1][0].set_title('RPCA Reconstruction')
    ax[1][0].set_xticks(())
    ax[1][0].set_yticks(())

    ax[1][1].imshow(kpca_restruct.reshape(120,160), cmap=plt.cm.gray)
    ax[1][1].set_title('KPCA Reconstruction')
    ax[1][1].set_xticks(())
    ax[1][1].set_yticks(())
    
    plt.tight_layout

    else:
        continue

Now those images are ready to go through the previous feature extraction methods. However, another feature extraction technique upon the images can solve this problem without crop out the coins.

SIFT¶

4.1 Introduction¶

4.1.1 What is SIFT?¶

The scale-invariant feature transform (SIFT) is a feature detection algorithm in computer vision to detect and describe local features in images. The algorithm was proposed by David Lowe in 1999 for the detection of local features in a digital image. It extracts features often called SIFT key points from the image in a circular region with an orientation. The SIFT detects key points from the image structures at multiple scales and rotation positions. Also the SIFT selected key points are invariant to translation, rotations, and rescaling of the image.

4.1.2 Why We Use It?¶

The heart of the coin sorting is feature selection and extraction mechanism. In general, coins are recognized from several different perspectives such as color, size or shape. The images we obtained may or may not give computer system an easy work for object recognition. Fortunately, using the Scale Invariant Feature Transform algorithm to handle the issues of rotations, scaling and illumination in a digital image is a wise choice. Those advantages are perfect match our needs as well as our dataset. Those images we used contains a lot of blank and some of them with notable difference in illumination. Using SIFT technique, the following challenges can be solved: 1. The noise in images due to different illumination condition. 2. Coins have stains, hole, or scratch on the surface area. 3. Coins are not always in the same spot of the images.

4.1.3 How does it work?¶

In [66]:
 #coding: utf-8
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
from imagedt.decorator import time_cost
import cv2
print ('cv version: ', cv2.__version__)


def bgr_rgb(img):
    (r, g, b) = cv2.split(img)
    return cv2.merge([b, g, r])


def orb_detect(image_a, image_b):
    # feature match
    orb = cv2.ORB_create()

    kp1, des1 = orb.detectAndCompute(image_a, None)
    kp2, des2 = orb.detectAndCompute(image_b, None)

    # create BFMatcher object
    bf = cv2.BFMatcher(cv2.NORM_HAMMING, crossCheck=True)

    # Match descriptors.
    matches = bf.match(des1, des2)

    # Sort them in the order of their distance.
    matches = sorted(matches, key=lambda x: x.distance)

    # Draw first 10 matches.
    img3 = cv2.drawMatches(image_a, kp1, image_b, kp2, matches[:100], None, flags=2)

    return bgr_rgb(img3)

@time_cost
def sift_detect(img1, img2, detector='surf'):
    if detector.startswith('si'):
        print ("sift detector......")
        sift = cv2.xfeatures2d.SURF_create()
    else:
        print ("surf detector......")
        sift = cv2.xfeatures2d.SURF_create()

    # find the keypoints and descriptors with SIFT
    kp1, des1 = sift.detectAndCompute(img1, None)
    kp2, des2 = sift.detectAndCompute(img2, None)

    # BFMatcher with default params
    bf = cv2.BFMatcher()
    matches = bf.knnMatch(des1, des2, k=2)

    # Apply ratio test
    good = [[m] for m, n in matches if m.distance < 0.5 * n.distance]

    # cv2.drawMatchesKnn expects list of lists as matches.
    img3 = cv2.drawMatchesKnn(img1, kp1, img2, kp2, good, None, flags=2)

    return bgr_rgb(img3)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    # load image
    image_a = cv2.imread('E:/CSE 7324/classification_dataset/all/5_1477145544.jpg')
